  "Opus One|Porterhouse": "Opus One — Oakville Bordeaux blend, dark fruit, mocha, cedar, dried violet, firm tannin. The firm tannin handles Porterhouse's dual strip-and-filet and the cedar plays against both lean-and-fatty sides. Strong collector Napa blend for Porterhouse — Mondavi-Rothschild on the dual-cut classic.",
  "Opus One|Prime Tartare": "Collector Napa Cab blend against raw-beef tartare — Opus One's firm-tannin full-body Bordeaux-blend structure buries raw-beef delicacy. Never pair. Route tartare to Pinot Noir, Beaujolais, lighter reds, or Champagne; keep Opus One for the steak course.",
  "Opus One|Rainbow Trout": "Opus One: this structured red's cassis-and-dark-fruit frame, firm tannin, and oak-driven weight meets this delicate seafood's mild, flaky flesh. The bold red's tannin shreds the fish's delicate flake, and the dark fruit clashes with briny sweetness. Textbook avoid — this is the classic red-meat-only territory.",
  "Opus One|Raventós Cava de NIT Rosé Brut": "Opus One: this structured red's cassis-and-dark-fruit frame, firm tannin, and oak-driven weight, considered as a bridge into this sparkling rosé's strawberry-and-brioche charm with crisp acidity. Avoid — the two drinks don't flow cleanly together.",
  "Opus One|Roast Half Chicken": "Opus One: this structured red's cassis-and-dark-fruit frame, firm tannin, and oak-driven weight meets this roasted chicken's savory, rich poultry-skin flavor. The bold red's tannin on roasted chicken — the wine outweighs the poultry unless the dish is intensely seasoned. Avoid — the bold red overwhelms chicken.",
  "Opus One|Roasted Red Pepper Chickpea": "Opus One: this structured red's cassis-and-dark-fruit frame, firm tannin, and oak-driven weight meets this sweet-earthy soup's mellow vegetable warmth. Acidic tomato or mild vegetable broth can't stand up to the bold red's dark-fruit density. Avoid — the soup shrinks next to the wine.",
