  "Seafood Tower|Inhibited": "Seafood Tower: this delicate seafood starter's briny-fresh sweetness meets this coffee-driven cocktail's bitter roast, rich texture, and dessert-adjacent sweetness. Coffee cocktail against a savory plate — wrong register entirely. Avoid — save for dessert.",
  "Seafood Tower|Japanese Gin": "Seafood Tower: this delicate seafood starter's briny-fresh sweetness meets this Japanese gin's yuzu, sakura, and delicate floral profile. Clean spirit against a delicate starter — aperitif-register more than pairing. Strong — clean aperitif lift.",
  "Seafood Tower|Jean-Pierre Grossot Chablis": "Chablis Chardonnay with oyster-shell minerality — the literal classical pairing for oysters. The mineral acid handles every component on the tower without needing to pivot between courses. Peak non-sparkling pour; reliable across oyster, shrimp, crab, lobster.",
  "Seafood Tower|Joseph Mellot Sancerre": "Loire Sauvignon Blanc — grapefruit and grass, bright acid. Handles the full spectrum of tower components; the grassy note doesn't overwhelm the delicate lobster. Classic Loire seafood logic at scale — safe across every bite.",
  "Seafood Tower|Lalo Silver": "Seafood Tower: raw oysters, shrimp, lobster meet additive-free craft. Strong; clean family-heritage character provides a craft through-line.",
  "Seafood Tower|Laurent Perrier Brut Rosé": "Seafood Tower: this delicate seafood starter's briny-fresh sweetness meets this sparkling rosé's strawberry-and-brioche charm with crisp acidity. Sparkling's bubbles and acid scrub the starter's fat while the bright frame lifts the plate. A headliner starter pour.",
  "Seafood Tower|Laurent Perrier Le Cuvée Brut": "Champagne acid cuts through briny oysters and cleans the palate between each component — oyster, shrimp, crab, lobster. Bubbles reset, acid delivers. The canonical pour for a seafood tower; position as the table's opening ceremony.",
  "Seafood Tower|Le Garenne Rosé": "Provence rosé — strawberry, citrus, clean. Works against the shellfish but doesn't peak the way sparkling does. Fine for the table splitting pours where one guest prefers still rosé over Champagne.",
